    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.12.2-4_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">2</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        1415 Race St.
                        <hi rend="underline">Denver, Colo.</hi>
                
                        Jan 28. 25.
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>My Dear Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>The above is my permanent address. Am more or less settled and painting again and glad to be back in Colorado. <del>again</del>.</p> 
                    
                <p>Yours of Dec. 3. sounds as tho<sic>though</sic> MacMillans<sic>Macmillans</sic> were going to <unclear>spread</unclear> themselves on your book and I'm delighted. So far I haven't had any proofs from Latham. I wish he would have them made so that I can work at my leisure and not rush the thing of coloring proofs.</p>
                    
                <p>I want a little help from you again. For the Mo. capitol I am making a character study of the "Facteur" or "Borgeouis" who <unclear>governed</unclear> the forts of the old fur companies and I am uncertain as to his costume. <unclear>Chittenden</unclear> + Coues both state that they wore a sort of uniform. (<unclear>Chittinden</unclear> Hist. <unclear>Am</unclear> Fur Trade. Vol 1 page 52) What was it like? I saw in the Mo. Hist. Society's collection a buckskin coat worn by Auguste Chouteau which might have been it altho<sic>although</sic> little was known about the coat It was <unclear>cut</unclear> like an ordinary coat of about 1820-30 but was fringed and decorated with quill <unclear>work</unclear>
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.12.2-4_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">3</fw>
                    
                    Cut somewhat like this: <figure><figDesc>Drawing of the coat described</figDesc></figure>
                    
                    In my decoration I have the facteur in the costume of fashion 1820-30 sitting at a table inside the fort with Indians + trappers about (whom he is interviewing) His hat is a grey beaver &#8212; tall. trousers tight fitting &#8212; watch <unclear>fobs</unclear> &#8212; top boots &#8212; ruff at neck of white linen, coat tight sleeved broad lapel velvet collar &#8212; waistcoat loud-colored. A shawl over his shoulders &#8212; a quill pen in his hand.</p>
                        
                <p>A capable square-jawed dandy in the wilderness was the type I tried to develop. Was I all wrong in this? I got the general impression from <unclear>Larfeuteus</unclear> years ago and begin to fear that I was mistaken.</p>
                        
                <p>I saw the architects of the Nebr. State Capital while in New York and registered with them. I also met Tack who is to decorate the Governer's Reception room. It looks as tho<sic>though</sic> the commissions would be awarded soon and I want mine. Am today writing G<unclear/> at Lincoln asking him to keep me posted.</p> 
                        
                <p>Well. more power to your <unclear/></p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>The<unclear/></salute>
                    
                    <signed>True</signed>
                    <note type="curatorial">Allen True</note>
                </closer>  
                        
            </div1>
            
